description.en:
*	ethnographic methods for collecting and creating empirical data (including interview, (participant) observation, different forms of ethnography and their application in the field of cultural heritage, and visual methods);
*	reflexivity and research ethics;
*	discourse analysis;
*	oral history as a method and practice; major theoretical developments, methodology and application areas in research and community work; based on the example of the Estonian National Museum;
*	principles for creating folklore archives and arranging folklore collections; uses of folklore collections in research, community work, tourism, education and cultural policy; based on the example of the Estonian Folklore Archives;
*	case studies.

objectives.en:
This course aims to provide students with 
*	broad-based knowledge about the main methods for creating and analysing ethnographic data;
*	skills in applying these methods professionally and ethically;
*	an overview of different memory institutions, principles for creating and organising their collections, and their application in identity processes, cultural policies and in meeting other goals;
*	opportunities to put knowledge and skills into practice in case studies conducted individually or in teams.

learning_outcomes.en:
Upon passing this course, students should
*	possess a systemic overview of the main ethnographic methods and their applicability;
*	be knowledgeable about reflexivity and ethical principles of ethnographic fieldwork;
*	possess skills in visually and audio-visually documenting folklore and cultural heritage; 
*	possess skills in conducting discourse analysis;
*	be familiar with different types of memory institutions and their functions, and with different approaches to arranging their work and collections;
*	be capable of applying the oral history method in research, and in applied projects aimed at communities and other specific groups.

description.et:
Reading response papers and other written assignments based on compulsory readings.
Length: 300-350 words per text (one article, book chapter, etc.)

- ability to identify and grasp authors' aims, main arguments, theoretical starting points, methods, and concepts succinctly;
- ability to create links between the readings;
- ability to display critical thinking skills
- correct formatting (citations!).

grade_evaluation.et:
1) Participation in biweekly classroom meetings (preferably no missed classes!) and online activities;
2) Punctual submission of reading responses;
3) Interview and its analysis;
4) (Participant) observation and documentation thereof; 
5) Reflexivity and ethics assignment
6) Methodological analysis of an ethnographic monograph.
